  "prompt": "How is the M27 IAR issued at the US Marines squad level? One for each fire-team, or mixed with the M249 SAW?",
  "response": "The M27 Infantry Automatic Rifle (IAR) is issued at the US Marine Corps squad level as part of their ongoing efforts to enhance their firepower and flexibility. The M27 IAR has largely replaced the M249 Squad Automatic Weapon (SAW) within the Marine Corps infantry squads.\n\nHere is how the M27 IAR is typically issued at the squad level:\n\n1. **Squad Composition**: A standard Marine Corps infantry squad consists of three fire teams, each led by a fire team leader.\n\n2. **Distribution**: Each fire team within the squad is equipped with one M27 IAR. This means that a standard infantry squad would have three M27 IARs, one per fire team.\n\n3. **Role of the M27 IAR**: The M27 IAR serves as the squad's automatic rifle, providing sustained suppressive fire. It is designed to be more accurate and controllable than the M249 SAW, making it suitable for both suppressive and accurate fire engagements.\n\n4. **Mixed with M249 SAW**: While the M27 IAR has largely replaced the M249 SAW in many Marine Corps infantry squads, some units might still retain the M249 SAW, particularly in specialized roles or based on specific mission requirements. However, the primary automatic weapon at the squad level is now the M27 IAR.\n\nIn summary, the M27 IAR is typically issued with one per fire team within a Marine Corps infantry squad, effectively replacing the M249 SAW in most standard configurations.",
